          "body": "The psalm's most theologically demanding stanza appeals to three historical mediators — Moses, Aaron, and Samuel — as evidence for the preceding claims. The selection is deliberate: Moses is the lawgiver and preeminent intercessor (Exodus 32:11–14; Numbers 14:13–20); Aaron is the high priest who stood between the living and the dead (Numbers 16:47–48); Samuel is the prophet-judge whose prayer turned the nation's course (1 Samuel 7:5–9; 12:23). All three called on Yahweh; all three were answered. The pillar of cloud (99:7) connects Moses and Aaron to Sinai revelation (Exodus 33:9; Numbers 12:5); Samuel's prophetic reception of the divine word is the implied extension. Three eras, three mediatorial functions, one pattern: call on the name, keep the testimonies, receive the answer. Verse 8 is the psalm's most complex verse: 'You were a forgiving God to them, and yet an avenger of their evil deeds.' Both halves are true simultaneously. Forgiveness (*nasa*) was real — Moses was restored after his outburst at the waters of Meribah (Numbers 20:11–12) well enough to be numbered among Yahweh's priests here. Yet the consequences of that same event excluded him from the land (Numbers 20:12). Aaron's sons Nadab and Abihu were consumed by fire for unauthorized offering (Leviticus 10:1–2). Samuel's sons were corrupt and disqualified him from dynastic succession (1 Samuel 8:3). Forgiveness and accountability are not sequential (first one, then the other) but simultaneous expressions of holiness applied to the same persons. The psalm refuses to let worship domesticate holiness into comfort."
