          "title": "The threefold 'Holy is He' — a refrain that accumulates rather than merely repeats",
          "body": "The psalm's three refrains are not ornamental repetition but a structured escalation. The first (99:3) closes the cosmic stanza with the bare predicate: 'Holy is He.' It answers the question implied by the nations' trembling — what is it about Yahweh that produces this response? His holiness. The second (99:5) closes the governance stanza: 'Holy is He.' Now holiness is disclosed as the ground of just governance — the same attribute that demands creaturely trembling also orders the King's love of justice. The third and final refrain (99:9) is the most expanded: 'For holy is the LORD our God.' Three changes are significant: the causal 'for' (*ki*) makes the refrain an explicit ground-statement for all commanded worship; the divine name is fully stated ('the LORD our God') — the covenant God, not merely the cosmic King; and the community claims Him as 'ours.' What began as a proclamation to the trembling nations ends as a confession of the covenant community standing at His holy hill. The movement from 'Holy is He' (distance) to 'Holy is the LORD our God' (intimate covenant claim) is the psalm's deepest pastoral movement."
