          "title": "Psalm 99 and the New Testament — the holy King enthroned in Christ",
          "body": "The enthronement psalms find their fullest meaning in the exaltation of Jesus Christ. Revelation 4:8 picks up the 'Holy, holy, holy' of the seraphic liturgy; Revelation 19:6 echoes the 'The LORD reigns' proclamation. Hebrews 1:3 describes the ascended Christ as seated at the right hand of the Majesty on high — the heavenly throne above the cherubim now occupied by the incarnate Son. The cherubim of the mercy seat, which in Psalm 99 frame Yahweh's earthly throne-point, are the same cherubim described by the author of Hebrews as 'overshadowing the mercy seat' (Hebrews 9:5) — the seat where Christ's own blood was offered as the ultimate resolution of the psalm's tension between forgiveness (*nasa*) and accountability (*naqam*). The God who was 'a forgiving God and yet an avenger of their evil deeds' in 99:8 has in Christ discharged both offices fully: He forgave the evil deeds by bearing them in the Son, and He avenged them by pouring out His wrath on the Son. The holy King's love of justice and His covenant mercy are no longer in tension — they are reconciled at the cross and vindicated in the resurrection. Worship at 'His holy hill' now means approaching Mount Zion in Hebrews 12:22 — 'the city of the living God, the heavenly Jerusalem' — through the mediatorial blood that speaks better things than Abel's (Hebrews 12:24)."
